Feature: bc-container engage auto-dismisses a blocking, escape-able interactive option screen before submitting the startup prompt, and logs what it dismissed as a host-discoverable warning

  Pins lead-q3uy. Composes with the autonomous-engagement path pinned by
  scenario 27 (features/bc-launcher/27-launch-with-startup-prompt-submits-prompt-autonomously.gherkin),
  the two-discrete-keystroke submission shape pinned by scenario 30
  (features/bc-launcher/30-launch-startup-prompt-sends-text-and-enter-as-two-discrete-invocations.gherkin),
  and the readiness barrier that gates engage pinned by scenario 34
  (features/bc-launcher/34-launch-runs-idempotent-readiness-barrier-before-engage.gherkin).

  Product context: the in-container agent runtime (Claude Code) may present a NEW
  interactive option/question screen at startup BEFORE the agent's prompt is ready
  to accept input — the motivating example is a "flicker-free rendering" opt-in
  screen, but the behavior must generalize to ANY such startup option screen, not
  only that one named option. Such a screen BLOCKS the input loop: the startup
  prompt cannot be committed (cf scenarios 27/30) because the agent is not yet at
  its prompt, so autonomous engage stalls indefinitely.

  This scenario pins the launcher's auto-dismiss behavior on the engage path. The
  launcher RECOGNIZES, on the tmux pane's rendered output, an interactive option
  screen that offers a dismiss/escape affordance — a yes/no, skip-able, or
  cancel-able prompt that has an escape path. For such a screen it sends an ESCAPE
  keystroke as a SEPARATE, discrete tmux send-keys invocation carrying the Escape
  key as its key payload (the same text-vs-key discipline scenario 30 pins for the
  Enter key: a discrete send-keys key name, never a literal byte embedded in a text
  payload) — NOT Enter, because Enter could select an unintended default. The
  abstract observable this scenario pins is "a discrete Escape key event, distinct
  from any Enter key event"; the BC owns the concrete tmux key-name token it maps
  that to (the conventional name is "Escape") and MUST document and echo that
  concrete key-name token in work_done. Product-authority policy: ONLY option
  screens that are safe to skip — i.e. that expose an escape/dismiss affordance —
  are auto-escaped; a screen with no escape affordance is NOT auto-confirmed and
  is not silently advanced with Enter. Everything the launcher auto-dismisses is
  CAPTURED and LOGGED as a WARNING to a host-discoverable location. Because a
  blocking option screen blocks the PROMPT, not the session — the in-container
  agent runtime IS up and its tmux pane IS rendering — the engage observability
  surface a host already reads without attaching ("bc-container monitor"; cf
  scenario 29) composes correctly as that location, so this scenario reuses it
  rather than inventing a new persisted warning path. The WARNING is discoverable
  on that monitor surface so a human can review what was auto-dismissed.

  After dismissal, engage proceeds and the real startup prompt is submitted
  exactly as scenarios 27 and 30 pin, with no host-side follow-up keystroke.

  @scenario_hash:f68d8199fef70fa7
  Scenario: engage recognizes a blocking escape-able option screen, sends Escape (not Enter) to dismiss it, then submits the startup prompt
    Given the shopsystem-bc-launcher BC is installed
    And no Docker container named "bc-shopsystem-messaging" is running
    And on engage the in-container agent runtime presents an interactive option screen that blocks the input prompt and exposes a dismiss/escape affordance
    When I run "bc-container launch shopsystem-messaging --startup-prompt 'bd prime'" and the launch command exits zero
    Then the launcher issues a discrete tmux send-keys invocation against the container driver carrying the Escape key as its key payload, targeting the tmux session named "agent" in container "bc-shopsystem-messaging", to dismiss the blocking option screen
    And that Escape-bearing invocation does not carry the Enter key in the same invocation
    And the launcher does not send an Enter keystroke to select a default on that blocking option screen
    And after the option screen is dismissed the startup prompt "bd prime" is submitted to the tmux session named "agent" with no host-side follow-up "bc-container inject" invocation required
    And the in-container agent transitions from the blocked option screen to actively processing the prompt "bd prime"

  @scenario_hash:f17f0fc747e44e47
  Scenario: an auto-dismissed option screen's content is captured and logged as a host-discoverable warning
    Given the shopsystem-bc-launcher BC is installed
    And no Docker container named "bc-shopsystem-messaging" is running
    And on engage the in-container agent runtime presents an interactive option screen that blocks the input prompt and exposes a dismiss/escape affordance
    When I run "bc-container launch shopsystem-messaging --startup-prompt 'bd prime'" and the launch command exits zero
    And I read the engage observability surface for the launch via "bc-container monitor shopsystem-messaging" from the host
    Then the launch surfaces a WARNING that an interactive option screen was auto-dismissed during engage
    And that warning captures the rendered content of the dismissed option screen so a human can review what was auto-dismissed
    And the warning is discoverable from the host without attaching into the container

  @scenario_hash:9d38d505fc8b5432
  Scenario: an interactive screen with no escape affordance is not auto-confirmed with Enter
    Given the shopsystem-bc-launcher BC is installed
    And no Docker container named "bc-shopsystem-messaging" is running
    And on engage the in-container agent runtime presents an interactive screen that blocks the input prompt and exposes no dismiss or escape affordance
    When I run "bc-container launch shopsystem-messaging --startup-prompt 'bd prime'" and the launch command runs the engage path
    Then the launcher does not send an Enter keystroke to advance the screen that has no escape affordance
    And between detecting the un-escapable option screen and returning from launch the launcher issues ZERO tmux send-keys invocations carrying the Enter key — and no keystroke of any kind — targeting the tmux session named "agent" in container "bc-shopsystem-messaging" while the un-escapable screen is present, as recorded by the container driver's send-keys recorder
    And the launcher does not auto-confirm a default on a screen that exposes no escape affordance
    And the launch surfaces a WARNING naming the un-escapable screen so a human can review it from the host
